'''Pavle Matejić''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Павле Матејић}}; {{circa}} 1770–1816), known as '''Paulj''' ({{lang|sr|Пауљ Матејић}}), was a [[Serbian Revolution]]ary that participated in the [[First Serbian Uprising]] (1804–13). Starting out as a captain under the command of [[Petar Dobrnjac]], Paulj was elevated to ''vojvoda'' (general) in the Gornja Mlava region upon showing his courage. He took part in the successful campaigns in the eastern parts of the [[Belgrade Pashaluk]], and the campaign to take [[Niš]] (1809).

==Life==
He was born in the village of [[Melnica, Petrovac|Melnica]],{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=331}} at that time part of the [[Požarevac]] ''[[Nahiye (Ottoman)|nahiya]]'' in the [[Sanjak of Smederevo]] ("Belgrade Pashaluk").

He became a ''buljubaša'' (captain) already by the beginning of the uprising, appointed by [[Petar Dobrnjac]].{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=331}} For his courage and other great traits, he was later appointed ''vojvoda'' (general) in Gornja Mlava.{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=331}} Paulj participated in the victories in the eastern parts of the [[Belgrade Pashaluk]] that strengthened rebel holding.{{sfn|Stojančević|2004|p=37}}

A rebel army led by commanders [[Miloje Petrović]], Petar Dobrnjac, [[Ilija Barjaktarević]], Paulj Matejić, [[Stevan Sinđelić]] and [[Hajduk-Veljko|Veljko Petrović]] arrived on {{OldStyleDateNY|27 April|15 April}} 1809 outside [[Niš]].{{sfn|Stojančević|2004|p=121}} During preparations for the takeover of Niš, Paulj made a [[trench]] above the village of [[Kamenica, Niš|Kamenica]].{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=331}} The trench, above the church, had two cannons.{{sfn|Mirčetić|1994|p=68}} It was one of eleven or twelve rebel trenches around the city.{{sfn|Mirčetić|1994|p=61}} On {{OldStyleDateNY|31 May|19 May}}, when the Ottomans [[Battle of Čegar|rushed on the Čegar hill]] defended by [[Stevan Sinđelić]], and ''vojvoda'' Miloje did not let anybody aid them, Paulj decided against the command and went for Čegar.{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=331}} Paulj did not reach in time; when the Ottomans had surrounded and overtook Sinđelić's trench, he decided to blow up the gunpowder magazine and kill everyone on the hill.{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=331}} Paulj and his small unit were defeated and forced to retreat, as others, to [[Deligrad]].{{sfn|Milićević|1888|pp=331–332}} He mostly stayed in Deligrad after this.{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=332}} The [[Serbian Ruling Council]] appointed Paulj the first permanent commander of [[Knjaževac|Gurgusovac (Knjaževac)]] after the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1812)]].{{sfn|Stojančević|1983|p=40}}

In the 1812–13 ''Protocol'' of [[Karađorđe]], there are ten numbers written for Paulj.{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=332}} In 1813, he fled to the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], while the Austrians sent him to stay in [[Leoben]] for a time.{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=332}} He returned to Serbia in 1815, and died in his home village.{{sfn|Milićević|1888|p=332}}

He begged for the hand of the daughter of [[Momir of Lučica]] for his son Budimir,<ref>{{cite book|last=Milićević|first=Milan|authorlink=Milan Milićević|year=1901|title=Додатак поменику од 1888. Знаменити људи у српскога народа који су преминули до краја 1900 г.|publisher=Srpska kraljevska štamparija|url=https://archive.org/stream/pomenikznamenit00miligoog#page/n899|p=180|ref=harv}} {{PD-icon}}</ref> and they married.

==Legacy==
There is a Serbian cultural association named after him. A statue of his was erected in his home village Melnica in 2004. A water mill in his ownership is today a recognized [[Cultural Heritage of Serbia|cultural monument]].

